lso for strengthening families, communities, and the nation as a whole. Offering a wealth of advice and recommendations, they explain:• the benefits of family leave, child care, and home visitation programs;• the damage that child abuse inflicts;• the vital importance of nutrition (and breast feeding) for pregnant women and young children;• the adverse effects that occur in misguided efforts to disseminate research too early;• and more.Written by experts in the field of early child development, care, and education, the book is essential reading for parents and policymakers alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBrainxResearchxSocial aspects. 0aCerveauxRecherchexAspect social. 0aChild development. 0aChild welfarexUnited States. 0aChild welfarezUnited States. 0aEnfantsxDéveloppement. 0aEnfantsxProtection, assistance, etcxÉtats-Unis. 0aFamily policyxUnited States. 0aInfantsxDevelopment. 0aNourrissonsxDéveloppement. 0aPolitique familialexÉtats-Unis. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Developmental / Child.2bisacsh1 aFinn-Stevenson, Matia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHall, Nancy W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300127393423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300127393.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles